Reasoning: The paper deals with the problem of reconstructing phylogenetic trees from mixed populations, which involves graph theory, combinatorics, and machine learning. The problem is characterized as a restricted class of spanning trees in a graph constructed from the input data, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The paper also proposes an algorithm to enumerate such trees in the important special case of cladistic characters, which involves machine learning and computational biology, and thus could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CE (Computational Biology and Bioinformatics) sub-categories. The paper also deals with cancer sequencing data, which involves database systems and data mining, and thus could belong to the cs.DB (Databases) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of reconstructing phylogenetic trees, which involves computational geometry and topology, and thus could belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category.
